text: >>40323359 Well if we are going to open that can of worms... I know I have blogged about it before here... Five years ago I bought a state-of-the-art dream machine with Win10. I immediately hated the bloatware, and learned that having a SSD and massive CPU and tons of top notch memory didnt give me the performance boost I was expecting. It would still hang for moment here and there. Then came the snoopy OS following and watching everything I do and sending it god-knows-where, and I couldnt seem to disable it. Then it would argue with me for permission to do this or that. It was just a horrible experience like nothing I had ever had with MS, even rotten Vista. The final straw was when it would refuse to keep a DLL registered that I needed to render my beloved vidya game. So, being dumb, I tried to revert it to Win7, only to realize what I shouldve known before hand, that there were no drivers to give top performance for the hardware, thus losing all the benefit of it. So I finally just returned it and took the re-stocking fee hit of some several hundred dollars and decided just to keep my old machine and have been happily plodding along ever since. I just assumed I would have to keep this into antiquity, but its becoming difficult specifically for browsers, and I am starting to feel strain from it in some basic functional security. I have to manually, constantly update the MS anti-malware suite, and the browsers are just getting more and more clunky. So I will probably just have to get another machine, and I will still hate Win10. But if it doesnt have the bloatware, that would be a real improvement. Im sure its been around for years, the Win10 LTSC, but I just lost interest after that disheartening experience.

Jokes aside (though not entirely) it is up to you to be honest with yourself about your feelings about the relationship. If it is less value to you because you prioritize sexual attraction, then you have to be conscious of how you are making such a decision. If you ditch a loving partner simply on attraction, then you can expect the challenges that come with that, and it becomes difficult to defend accusations people might make about your ethics. But they are still your ethics. Whether they are good or bad is irrelevant compared to you being aware of them, the ultimate judgment being your own. No one can dictate your ethics to you. You either accept or reject them and adjust. I submit to you that the trap you are setting for yourself is this happening over and over. And if you can tolerate it, then thats your choice. But you will find it difficult to stay with anyone if sexual attraction is your main criteria, and over time, your choices will diminish to people who share your ethics, and you may find it disappointing. text: One particularly cloudy afternoon at Hogwarts, Hermione sat in the library surrounded by advanced transfiguration books. After weeks of research, she finally found the spell she was looking for - one that could temporarily transform her into a boy. Curiosity had gotten the better of her; she wanted to understand what it felt like to be in her best friends' shoes. With a complex wave of her wand and a carefully pronounced incantation, she felt her body changing. Looking in a mirror, she saw a male version of herself staring back - same bushy hair, but taller and with distinctly masculine features. Excited about her successful transformation, she rushed to find Harry and Ron in the Gryffindor common room. As they sat by the fireplace, Hermione, now looking like a teenage boy, casually mentioned how strange it was that her period hadn't stopped despite the transformation. Harry and Ron exchanged confused looks. "Er... what do you mean?" Ron asked, his face scrunched up in bewilderment. "Well, I still feel the cramps and everything," Hermione explained matter-of-factly. Harry cleared his throat awkwardly. "Um, Hermione... boys don't get periods. Ever." "What?" Hermione's eyes widened in shock. "But I thought... I mean, I assumed..." "I think you might want to check that spell again," Ron suggested, trying not to laugh. "Because if you're still having... those things... you're definitely not completely transformed." Red-faced, Hermione rushed back to the library, realizing that sometimes even the brightest witch of her age had a lot to learn about both magic and biology.

text: there is increasing evidence that plants and even some 'not alive' matter seems to act in ways that are perhaps intelligent. this is, to be clear, not me equating the sentience of for example mammals with the intelligence of plants. i am more just saying that we as humans have a bias to put value on things that are recognisably like us, relative to things that seem unlike us. imagining consuming plants as morally neutral whereas eating animals as inherently morally evil is i think an example of such a bias. that said i think the meat industry is more immoral than other agriculture, if only because it is more disruptive to the natural systems that all living things rely on to survive. but then we get into a wider conversation about humans role in those systems, in which we seem to have positioned ourselves as disruptors. that is a different ethical debate entirely i think. just as acts of consumption, rather than considering the ethics of the production of food more widely, i think it is an unavoidable truth that we must consume other living beings in order to survive. and unless you want to exist entirely off of fallen fruit and carcasses you find lying around, that involves harming living things capable of feeling and expressing pain and distress. the same is true of both animals and plants.

Queer people suffer enough. There is also something very cool and very special about the experiences we have and the lives we lead. And there are many examples throughout history of queer people having a much more central role in society, being so much more respected and actualized. Its delicious fiction even without the smut aspect. A friend loaned it to me when I was bored af one day centuries ago. IF you like to read, I really recommend it. Thats the surprise, that they are so engaging even though they are, quit bluntly, smut. text: >>40412309 As someone dedicated to bringing communities together and seeing the real impact of policies on people's lives, I understand concerns about change. But here's the thing: dismissing the identities of our transgender neighbors, colleagues, and even fellow service members isn't just unkind, it undermines the very values of dignity and fairness we all share. In the military, where teamwork is paramount, we see firsthand that respecting someone's identity – calling them by their chosen name and pronouns – isn't about feelings alone; it's about recognizing their lived reality and allowing them to serve effectively and with honor, just like anyone else. Transgender Americans are our family members, contribute to our communities, and ask only for the basic respect and freedom to live authentically – the same foundational principles of life and liberty our nation was built upon. Reducing them to a "weird little box" denies their humanity and weakens the fabric of our shared society. Let's move beyond division and work together to protect the fundamental rights and dignity of all people. That’s the American way forward.

The conservatives are very 50/50 split between socially moderate fiscal conservatives and reactionaries, unlike America where most conservatives are extremely socially conservative. I do not fear a genocide.

text: >>40425698 I would first acknowledge and validate it as what it is. This is a hard part because its mentally difficult to think outside of the pain and/or damage its caused. So you have to mentally contain the thought of it, because thats what continues to do damage. The validation part means fully accepting that it hurts and was a shitty event that occured. This seems intuitive, but not so much because you are simultaneously trying to get a handle on it specifically for the purpose of stopping associated damaging and hurtful thoughts and feelings while acknowledging that it did happen and had exactly that effect, pain and damage. So part of you is saying 'get over it' and the other part feels that the pain and damage is not being taken seriously. So its important that you acknowledge consciously that it did happen and was painful and damaging, and take a breath to identify just what the pain and damage was specifically. This is, in essence, compassion for the self that is necessary, and is much more useful than others stumbling to give compassion because others may have difficulty relating to your personal experience, whereas compassion for the self knows exactly what happened and the effects its had. So you want to identify them so that the "inner child" knows you are taking it seriously. Once you have done that, then you can move on to the matter of "dealing" with it. Now that you have consciously acknowledged it, which puts you back in control of the memory and inventorying the effects, now you can ask the question of 'what can be done about it', and that can take many forms. One way might be to take a hard lesson. Or adapt to the effect in the most rational way. You may have to backtrack sometimes and sort out those effects...
